Introduction And Goal

This project is to build 2 movie recommender systems based on Movielense 1M Datasets.
And for each movie recommender systems, there will be two schemes/methods.
- System 1 recommends 10 popular movies in each genre,and the recommended movies in each genre will be invariant in spite of different users. - System 2 recommends 10 movies based on the ratings the user provided on some movies. It is based on the ratings among similar users or items.

There are two files related in this project: movies and ratings datasets.

  • movies.dat [Github_link]
  • ratings.dat [Github_link]

ratings data

movies data In movies.dat, some movie names contain single colon (:), so the method above does not work.

Dist of Genres

First cretae a bibary indicator for the 18 genres for each movie.

Then we can output historograms of the 18 genres baesd on movies or based on ratings.

About half of the movies belong to only one genre; about one-third are categorized into two genres; a few are categorized into more than four genres. The movie “The Transformers” (1986) are categorized into six genres: Action, Animation, Children’s, Sci-Fi, Thriller, and War.

For illustration purpose only, let’s assume movies contains all the movies available to users from 1919 to 2000. Then we can compute the cumulative percentages of the 18 genres over year from 1919 to 2000 and store them in the 81-by-19 matrix tmp. For example, till 2000, users can access about 7.8% Action, 4.4% Adventure, 25% Drama, etc. A graphical display of such CDF over 10 generes are displayed below.

# range(movies$Year) % 1919 to 2000
tmp = data.frame(Year = movies$Year, genre_matrix) %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarise_all(sum)
tmp[,-1] = apply(tmp[, -1], 2, cumsum)
tmp[,-1] = tmp[,-1]/sum(tmp[nrow(tmp), -1])
print(round(tmp[nrow(tmp),-1], dig=3))

Movie Recommender

System 1: A simple Movie Recommender by Genre

System 1 recommends movies to users in the selected genre. This system answers question, such as in this genre, what are the top 10 most popular movies? There are two options/schemes for this system, including scheme 1 and scheme 2.

  • Scheme 1 defines popular movies as the ones which are most rated. Put it in another way, they are the movies which got the largest number of reviews.
  • Scheme 2 defines popular movies as the ones which are highly rated. They are the ones that have the top average ratings across users.

Recommendation Scheme 1:Define most popular as most rated movies

I write csv files for top 10 movies for each genre. Here, I will show the last genre in datatable for illustration purpose.

System 2: A more sophiscated Movie Recommender (item-based & user-based)

Tasks a movie recommender system deals with:
- To predict ratings for movies the user has not rated yet. - To make a list of recommended movies

There are two basic architectures for a recommendation system:

  • Content-Based, which focus on features of the items and the similarity among the items based on these features
  • Collaborative-Filtering, which focus on the relationship between users and items.The similarity would be based on the user ratings among the items.We need to identify similar users and make recommendation according to this. I will utilize collaborative-filtering in this project

Collaborative-Filtering: UBCF & IBCF

  • User Based Collaborative Filtering (UBCF) recommends items on the basis of the similarity in ratings among users.

  • Item Based Collaborative Filtering (IBCF) recommends items on the basis of the similarity in ratings among items.

Workflow

  • Preprocessing
  • Measure similarity of users/items.
    • Utility Matrix structure: The columns will be different movies, and the row will be different users, the value will be the ratings that each user gave the each movie.
    • Build utility martix in 2 ways:
      1. Jaccard Distance vs Cosine Distnce Jaccard Distance: 1-Jaccard similarity = 1-intersection size/union size *100%
        Rounding the data: 3,4,5 as 1 and 1,2 as unrated
        Cosine Distance: Larger cosine implies a smaller angle/ distance. disadvantage treat missing value more like negative rating
        Normalizing Ratings: subtracting average rating from each rating
      2. User similarity vs Item similarity Use user similarity: For user I, Find k users who are most similar to this user. Average their normalized ratings on each movies and make recommendation. Use item similarity: For item J, Find m items which are most similar to this item, and take average rating.
      3. Clustering users and items: CLuster based on user and items. If ratings in the corresponding cluster is not blank, make recommendation use that cluster. If blank, use item or user cluster.
  • Fit realRatingMatrix to UBCF & IBCF models
  • Perform 10 fold cross validation and Validating Recommender Systems using RMSE

Fit UBCF & IBCF models

What to consider?

  • Normalization: The goal of normalization is to make the ratings in same scale so each user’s rating will appear equaly important. we need to normalize our data, in case some users tend to always give high reviews or low reviews. I use Z-score normalization, which is normalization by deviation and sample mean, it gives fixed sample variance, and it makes it is easier and faster for future computation.
  • The nearest neighborhood size I picked is 25. I check 10 and it gives a worse RMSE.
  • similarity metric I use is cosine distance, it measures similarity by the angel between two vectors.
  • The prediction is based on a weighted average, it computed with the sample deviation and sample/neighors mean ratings.
  • There will be missing values after running the algorithm. One way to deal with this is to expand the size of neighborhoods, since there will be more movies ratings and therefore more movies maybe included. However, this may be at a cost a lower prediction accuracy.
i = paste0('u', ratings$UserID)
j = paste0('m', ratings$MovieID)
x = ratings$Rating
tmp = data.frame(i, j, x, stringsAsFactors = T)
Rmat = sparseMatrix(as.integer(tmp$i), as.integer(tmp$j), x = tmp$x)
rownames(Rmat) = levels(tmp$i)
colnames(Rmat) = levels(tmp$j)
Rmat = new('realRatingMatrix', data = Rmat)

This UBCF model: - User-Based Collaborative Filtering is applied. - Z-score normalization is applied. - Using Cosine distance to measure similarity - Use the ratings of the 25 most similar users for predicting new ratings

This IBCF model: - Item-Based Collaborative Filtering is applied. - Z-score normalization is applied. - Using Cosine distance to measure similarity - Use the ratings of the 25 most similar users for predicting new ratings

# Split into training and test data
# create evaluation scheme splitting taking 90% of the date for training and leaving 10% for validation or test
e <- evaluationScheme(Rmat, method="split", train=0.9, given=15)
# creation of recommender model based on ubcf
Rec.ubcf <- Recommender(getData(e, "train"), "UBCF")
# creation of recommender model based on ibcf for comparison
Rec.ibcf <- Recommender(getData(e, "train"), "IBCF")
# making predictions on the test data set
p.ubcf <- predict(Rec.ubcf, getData(e, "known"), type="ratings")
# making predictions on the test data set
p.ibcf <- predict(Rec.ibcf, getData(e, "known"), type="ratings")
# obtaining the error metrics for both approaches and comparing them
error.ubcf<-calcPredictionAccuracy(p.ubcf, getData(e, "unknown"))
error.ibcf<-calcPredictionAccuracy(p.ibcf, getData(e, "unknown"))
error <- rbind(error.ubcf,error.ibcf)
rownames(error) <- c("UBCF","IBCF")
error
##          RMSE      MSE       MAE
## UBCF 1.161284 1.348582 0.9095466
## IBCF 1.474440 2.173973 1.1397260

Cross Validation and Conclusion

Performed 10 fold cross validation on my ratings data.

# create evaluation scheme splitting taking 90% of the date for training and leaving 10% for validation or test
e <- evaluationScheme(Rmat, method="cross", k=10, given=10)
# creation of recommender model based on ubcf
ubcf_result <- evaluate(e, "UBCF", type="ratings", parameter = list(normalize = 'z-score', method = 'cosine', nn = 25))

The resulted RMSE for UBCF,IBCF and POPULAR model shows that POPULAR model has the best result and then UBCF, and IBCF. POPULAR model is actually belong to system one since it is averages always give same result for all users. Therefore, for system 2, I will pick UBCF as my model for my application, not only because it has higher accuracy then IBCF but also it is faster.

result=rbind(avg(ubcf_result),avg(ibcf_result),avg(pop_result))
rownames(result)=c('UBCF','IBCF','POPULAR')
